76561198412517946,Recommended,292780,34548993,Posted: 28 August,all,dallin,"In my opinion, Pajama Sam was the best series Humongous ever made, featuring imaginative settings, witty writing, and clever gameplay. Now, I personally think that Pajama Sam 2 isn't quite as good as the first and third games in the series, but that isn't saying much because this is an excellent adventure game. In this entry, Sam decides that he's had enough of a scary thunderstorm, and sets out to put a stop to Thunder and Lightning, who turn out to be sisters in charge of the world's weather. Finding a massive complex called World Wide Weather, he sneaks inside and has an accident that sends the weather operations into turmoil, and now he must find the four missing parts to bring the weather factories back on line, before Thunder and Lightning lose their jobs.One point of criticism I have is that the big conundrum in the game  is all Sam's fault. That doesn't hurt my enjoyment of the game, but I don't like it when the main objective of game is undoing the protagonist's mistake. It would have been better if Sam had arrived just after things went awry, lending some mystery to what caused the problem; maybe Foster Boondoggle, who never appears in-person in the game, could secretly be the perpetrator who we confront at the end.Otherwise, the game is just what you'd expect from a Pajama Sam game: exploring a boy's wild imagination, populated by characters who are mostly living furniture and in a fun, nonsensical setting. The game world is a mix of industrial and corporate environments, contrasting with both PJ Sam 1 and 2. You'd think this would be boring, but the game is so imaginative that it's every bit as fun to explore as the other games. Something else that just occurred to me is the first three PJ Sam games each occur at different times of the day: PJ Sam 1 is at night, 2 is during the day, and 3 is during twilight. Having a fourth game kind of screws up that pattern, but oh well.All in all, this is a great game for kids, and also for any fan of adventure games. In fact, I'd recommend any of the Pajama Sam or Spy Fox games for any adventure gamer, regardless of age."
